      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Tenant Rights During a Sale Campaign in Queensland: What Sellers and Agents Must Follow
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Selling a tenanted investment property in Queensland is not the same as selling a vacant home. Tenants have legal protections that govern when and how you can access the property, and sellers who do not understand those rules tend to create problems for themselves mid-campaign.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>When you sell a tenanted investment property in Queensland, you do not get to treat the property as though it is vacant just because you want to run a sale campaign. The tenant's rights under the Residential Tenancies and Rooming Accommodation Act 2008 (RTRA Act) remain fully in force throughout the sales process. The agent conducting the campaign is bound by the same notice and access rules as the property manager. Sellers who assume that a decision to sell overrides the tenant's rights will run into friction at best, and formal complaints or QCAT applications at worst.</p>

      <p>This is not a reason to avoid selling a tenanted property. Tenanted investments sell regularly and successfully in Brisbane. But they require a different approach from the start, and sellers who manage this well tend to have smoother campaigns and cleaner results.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Notice requirements for open homes and inspections</h2>
      <p>The RTRA Act requires that tenants receive at least 24 hours written notice before each entry for an open home, private inspection, or photography session. Entry is permitted only between 8am and 6pm. These are not guidelines or courtesies: they are statutory requirements. An agent who books an unannounced open home or shows up with 30 minutes notice is in breach of the Act, and the tenant is within their rights to refuse entry in that circumstance.</p>

      <p>On frequency, the Act limits routine entry to once per week. This means you cannot run three open homes per week without the tenant's written agreement. For a typical sales campaign, one open home per week is the maximum you can insist upon. If the tenant agrees in writing to additional access, that agreement is binding. But it must be an agreement freely given, and sellers should not pressure tenants into agreeing to access frequency that suits the campaign rather than the tenant.</p>

      <p>In practice, this means campaign planning for a tenanted property needs to account for these constraints from the outset. You schedule one open home per week, you provide 24 hours notice for each, and you work around those parameters. This is a legitimate and workable campaign structure, not a serious impediment to selling.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What tenants can and cannot refuse</h2>
      <p>Tenants can refuse entry if the required notice has not been given. They can refuse unreasonable requests, such as access outside the permitted hours or at a frequency that exceeds what the Act allows without their agreement. They can refuse to accept an unreasonable number of additional inspection requests beyond the statutory minimum.</p>

      <p>What tenants cannot do is blanket-refuse all access. If a seller provides the required 24 hours written notice and requests entry at a reasonable time within the permitted hours, the tenant is not entitled to refuse. If a tenant does prevent reasonable access after proper notice, the agent can make an urgent application to the Queensland Civil and Administrative Tribunal (QCAT) for an order requiring the tenant to allow entry. QCAT applications are a last resort and the process takes time, so the aim should always be to avoid reaching that point through early communication and a cooperative relationship with the tenant.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to work with a cooperative tenant</h2>
      <p>The most effective approach to a tenanted sale campaign is to involve the tenant from the beginning and to acknowledge explicitly that the sale process is a disruption to their home. Tenants who feel respected and informed tend to be cooperative. Tenants who feel that they are being managed around rather than spoken to tend to become problems.</p>

      <p>A practical first step is a direct conversation with the tenant before the campaign launches: explaining when open homes are planned, how much notice they will receive, what the photography session involves, and whether you can accommodate any preferences they have around timing. Some sellers offer a rent reduction or other acknowledgement for the period of the campaign as a gesture of goodwill. This is not legally required but it can shift the dynamic significantly. A tenant who has been treated fairly is more likely to keep the property in good condition during the campaign and less likely to create friction around access.</p>

      <p>On photography, tenants' belongings will be visible in the property. Discuss this with the tenant before the photographer attends. Most tenants will agree to tidy the property for photography if asked in advance and with reasonable notice. Some sellers offer to bring in a professional stylist to supplement what is there, which can work well if the tenant is open to it. Springing a photography session on a tenant without prior discussion is likely to produce images that do not serve the campaign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Can you end the tenancy to sell?</h2>
      <p>This is one of the most common questions from sellers of tenanted investment properties, and the answer is: only in limited circumstances.</p>

      <p>A seller cannot terminate a tenancy simply because they want to sell. The tenancy agreement is a legal contract between you and the tenant, and a decision to put the property on the market does not entitle you to terminate it early. The lease runs with the property: if it has not expired by settlement, the buyer takes over as landlord and inherits the tenancy agreement in full.</p>

      <p>The exception is where the buyer intends to occupy the property as their principal place of residence. In that case, the seller (or the buyer, after contract) can give the tenant notice to vacate. For a periodic tenancy, the minimum notice period is two months. For a fixed-term tenancy, the lease must expire before a notice to vacate based on the buyer's owner-occupancy intent can take effect: you cannot end a fixed-term lease early on this ground.</p>

      <p>It is worth understanding the difference between these two scenarios when you are marketing the property. A property being marketed as suitable for owner-occupiers may attract a buyer who needs the tenant to leave, and if the tenancy is fixed-term with twelve months remaining, that buyer may not be able to take possession on their preferred timeline. Setting correct expectations in the marketing and being transparent about the lease details from the outset avoids surprises in the negotiation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Selling with a fixed-term tenancy in place</h2>
      <p>Selling with a fixed-term tenancy is a straightforward transaction for buyers who intend to hold the property as an investment. They take over as landlord at settlement, collect the rent, and manage the property through the existing tenancy agreement. In Brisbane's inner east, where rental vacancy is consistently low and yields on well-located houses and townhouses remain attractive to investors, a tenanted property with a quality tenant and a lease in good order is often actively appealing to investor buyers.</p>

      <p>The disclosure obligation for sellers here is clear: buyers should be provided with the tenancy agreement, the current rent, the bond amount, and the lease end date before they sign a contract. This information belongs in the contract disclosure documents, and buyers will expect to see it before they commit. Sellers who are transparent about the tenancy details give buyers confidence. Sellers who try to obscure or minimise the tenancy details create uncertainty that tends to show up as a lower price or a conditional contract with more room for the buyer to renegotiate.</p>

